<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>One wanted to abstain in the first place. But Ten didn't sufficiently defend Alpha-9 to his liking, and she didn't say anything. One couldn't see the point of standing by and letting the experiment unfold when Ten, its biggest backer, seemed to have given up championing it.</p>
<p>When she <em>did</em> break silence, and made an argument, One decided to abstain. It helped that it would've been politically better for her to apologize and back off to avoid censure, but she didn't. (She took a leap of faith.)</p>
<p>Six was already ambivalent, and felt similarly to One, and also felt One's opinion was worth taking into account, so he changed to abstain as well (One's vote had swayed him to the Nays in the first place).</p>
<p>And Seven is&#8230; Seven. She was already helping Alpha-9, despite her initial Nay vote. So she was willing to change her vote to Support once One and Six had sent a message that it was tactically viable to do so.</p>
<p>At that point, Alpha-9 passed. The rest was just Eight fucking up. And it STILL doesn't pass with a majority 7 votes.</p>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p>I've added a couple cut lines back in to indicate that Ten didn't say very much until her mini-speech, because I see that they're necessary. (That doesn't necessarily fix it for everyone, mind you.)</p>
<p>Feedback appreciated.</p>

							</div>

								
